title: How to study physics to get 150 marks in the NEET - Quora

response.answer_text: This is going to be quite a long of an answer. (From 44 to 166 ) (Again, my backstory: I used to hate Physics ,scored 44 in NEET 18 ,but through practice and understanding Physics, I started loving it and scored166 in neet 2019)  Here's a detailed point to point description of how you can do it as well. 1. Be thorough with the basic math involved: Basic math plays a key role in solving many questions. Integration, differentiation, trigonometry and a few identities, geometric progressions and estimation is important in this section. Do not go for the complex integrations / differentiations basic rules including multiplication and division will suffice. Vectors are also really important , be thorough nwith dot and cross products also keep important properties in mind. 2. Get the concepts crystal clear: Each and every part has to be remembered conceptually. Take for example, this statement "A force doesn't decide the trajectory of a particle." Imagine yourself throwing a stone ,done? There are numerous ways you can throw it and in all of them its trajectory would be different. Visualization is really helpful as well. 3. Be regular and at par with your coaching classes: Practice each day , for example you learnt Biot-Savart's law today , practice 10 questions on it , not only it will help you grasp the concepts but make you faster. 4. Mark questions for review: It is not possible to revise all the questions when you need to refer a chapter for test , so when you solve exercise for the first time itself mark all those questions that you feel were difficult , or involved multiple concepts , or took exceptionally long time. 5. Previous years' questions are important: Solve the previous years' questions at least TWICE. These questions will give you a good idea of the questions that are asked in the real exam. 6. Practice makes physics perfect: The more you practice , the faster you get. The faster you get , the more accurate you will be . Speed and accuracy are the outcomes of practice. There's no substitute for practice. 7. Get your doubts cleared regularly: Whatever doubts arise in your mind , get them cleared , even if they are silly if you didn't understand ask your teachers to explain it again , get your doubts cleared within 3 days ( before you forget them) 8. Try different approaches to the same question: Play with physics ,try different methods , you might find out a easier /much faster one. Don't stick to the textbook approach. 9. Make short notes: At the end of each chapter, take a notebook, and make short notes on it. The short notes must include all the important formulae, conceptual points , and some of the best questions you feel which would help you revise a chapter. These will help you revise a lot of chapters in less time. 10. Make weekly and monthly revision plans: It's quite natural to forget the things which are left untouched for a long time , so to prevent this , make short and long term revision plans. This will keep you in touch with all of the physics chapters until the exam day. 11. Lastly , stop fearing and start loving physics: NEET physics is not a hard nut to crack. Its simple and requires persistence and patience, the improvements are gradual and can be seen in long term. Low marks shouldn't demotivate you at all, learn form mistakes and try not to repeat them. • Now , lets have a peep into the paper solving strategy in the exam.  There are 45 questions in the physics section. (wow Parv , what a great thing you told us!)  • Start with the super duper easy peasy questions , they typically take less than a minute or 1 minute at max. In NEET 18 there were 13 such questions where you need not use the pen to solve them, literally.  • Alright, you've solved , say, 10 questions 35 to go . Now go for the questions which you think you can solve within 1–2 minute(s) . These questions comprise of the ones which are directly formula based. And their options are not really close , so calculations would be easier using estimation. 22 to 25 questions are of this type  • Now those 10 questions that you left must be the ones you can’t make out. Or they must have really lengthy calculations or some formula you don't remember. These questions should be done in the end of paper when you have 20–30 minutes left. Out of these you might be able to solve 5- 7 questions.  • Physics normally takes more time than bio or chem so it's a bonus if you complete chem and bio within 1.5 to 1.75 hours. The more time left , the more calm you are which means less negatives.  • Letting go is better than negatives , always remember that.  • When it comes to physics practice makes all the difference the more you've practiced the easier it will get.  That's pretty much it!  Best of luck!  Parv

It's truth, you have to believe me. Physics of neet as compared to any other entrance test is relatively easy. There are two strategies to handle physics : Fundamental strategy : Good hold on theory : concepts should be very clear. Go through the topics weightagewise. Heavy topics needs very hole to be mended; less important topics - take an overall idea of concept. Practice (two phase) : first phase : if you are attempting NEET For the first time then follow this - need to go through beginners questions (elementary questions - topic wise).Second phase : after all the theory is done + beginners questions are done - then start the hard one. The questions that make you sweat hard. Take jee questions too. Allen modules. Aakash modules. Guide books. Anything you get take up that.Note : remember one thing : don't go flirting with books, I mean don't change your study material again and again - decide one when you start (a good one) then stick to it for a year (whatever your time period is).Revisions : it's varies from student to student : find out your best way to revise the material at regular intervals. I'll share mine : I just take up random chapters which are attractive, first round goes by theory + hard question. I finish all syllabus without revision (seriously I don't forget things easily). At last when All syllabus is done say December /January, then I keep 3 markers based on level of questions (red-must revise whatever the situation is, green-no need to hang up read the answer and move on, blue-your choice have enough do it otherwise if left no problem). I practice those questions once again.Keep time boundary : while doing them that is last time (revision) keep an alarm of an hour (I do) and in an hour if you manage out 60 questions (all kind - easy to tough) then you are going good. Stop as soon as alarm rings no excuse. Really don't you dare give excuses!! Calculate your score - this is your level!! Damn - improve that!!Test : take up test (sweetheart!!) - any kind - if you are involved in self study then keep alarm and close the room - if you are coaching joined then go attend all tests - if you are clueless then join online test series - do whatever but attempt test - test of 180 questions (Complete with physics chemistry biology). Advanced strategy : The things mentioned above are pretty known - everyone will say that but the difference is marked here. This section will really tell you about your success. Practice questions without pen and paper. If needed have a pencil and use header and footer section of your book /guide /module /whatever. Use corners for calculations. If you are unable to do that in first attempt, don't worry, let it be so. But in revision interval follow this. Hard. Harder. Sweat. But don't use pen and paper. Deadline :not in January /February /March /April. Nope!! Until then you have to sharpen yourself.Don't you ever dare to use a calculator to calculations - whatever they be - easy, medium, hard. Mark my words the person addicted to calculator can never speed up later. From the first day itself stop that, If you wanna succeed. You had a habit, it will be hard for you initially, but later on calculator will irritate you.Don't just get dragged by formula everytime. Try to use smarter tricks. I have some but you need to develop your own. A question from gravitation can be solved by units and measurements tricks. A question from magnetism can be solved by kinematics tricks. Develop your own inter - woven tricks. Shuffle the topics. Everything is interlinked, try to handle concepts like DJ. Mix them. It will help you.Keep clear to yourself what formula is to be applied for what situation. There are similar situations where usually average students get confused and unable to figure out which formula would actually work here. So, keep Crystal clear margins.Quick : quick : quick : go fast : hurry up : don't get stuck on question : no way : roaming around the answer but unable to get to point just leave it : move dear. I know it's tough to leave a question when you are just somewhere around it. But you have to leave it after you have given it the time it deserves.Many more tricks : listen, the competition is not about knowledge ha!! Everybody is intelligent here!! The competition is about tricks + speed - that's it!! And nothing else.It's a great legendary GAME!! Yes legendary!! Many had gone through this. Some lost the battle. Some won. Some disappointed. Some angry. Some died (suicide). Some lived. Some… Just a game. Just a game. Play it All the best Sandeep K

Many Medical students find Physics section difficult since it contains a wide variety of theoretical concepts and numerical problems. Most of the you guys have developed a habit of learning everything. This may help you in Biology but not in Physics. When you try to study Physics without having any practical edge to your preparation plan,you feel that you have understood all the concepts but during ypur examinations you won’t be able to apply the same. So, to overcome this problem below I have provided the perfect study plan and preparation tips to crack Physics.  *NEET Physics comprises of following topics*(very very very important trust me) MechanicsElectrodynamicsModern PhysicsHeat and ThermodynamicsOpticsSHM and WavesBefore you get to know the Preparation Tips to crack Physics Section, let’s have a look at the weightage each topic contains:  preparation is to check the Physics Syllabus and Exam Pattern. You also need to be aware of the marking scheme for Physics Section in NEET Exam. Some basic tips you need to know.. Clear Your ConceptsAccording to Previous Year Papers, Mechanics, Heat & Thermodynamics, Electrodynamics and Modern Physics are the most important topics in Physics. So for your Physics Preparation, you must first clear the concepts related to these topics. Once you clear all the concepts, you are now ready to follow the next step.    PC- Internet Learn FormulasFormulas are the backbone of Physics. Learning Formulas is the most important step while preparing Physics. So, try to learn those formulas daily. Make a small diary and write all the Physics Formula for NEET. Now, you just need to revise those formulas daily, once or twice a day. Refer Best BooksFor your preparation, you need to refer best Physics Books for NEET Exam.You must me heard everyone's saying that NCERT is the best book to prepare for NEET Exam. Maybe it is…But personally I never used ncert for physics.. Instead of that I used DC pandey.. I agree most of the questions are asked from NCERT book. But for practicing numerical problems, you may refer other books as well. I solved USS.. I agree it’s lengthy book but It covers every type question. You can give it a try tgen you'll know. Baki apni apni shraddha:-D Solve Previous Year Question PapersThe best way to prepare for Physics is to solve Previous Year Question Papers. Solving these Physics Questions will help you identify the type of questions asked in the NEET Exam. It also improves your speed and accuracy. So, solve as many question papers as possible and get yourself prepared for the exam. Make NotesDuring your preparation , you need to make notes of all the important formulas, theorems and concepts. Physics Notes for NEET will help you to learn the concepts faster and will also help you in your last-minute preparation.  Take Online Mock TestsTaking Online Mock Tests will help you identify your level of preparation that how much you have prepared for the exam. It will also help you identify your weak areas.Improve Your Weak AreasTry to improve your weak areas. Focus more on the topics in which you are weak. Make a list of those topics and try to improve those. You must start with the most important topics of Physics and after that prepare for the less important ones.So, you must start with the most important topics for Physics Preparation. It is also important to know the no. of questions asked from every chapter in the NEET Exam 2020 in Physics Section. So, below is the list of chapters from which the questions were asked in NEET Physics Exam. *pink mark- very important chapters *  Also How to Study Physics for NEET: Topic-wise Preparation Tips- [math]Motion of System of Particles and Rigid Body[/math]Questions for finding torque and Moment of inertia of regular bodies using parallel and perpendicular axes theorem is considered an important section in Physics. Practice more for these types of questions. Also practice numericals based on conservation of angular momentum and rolling motion. Circular Motion questions can be easily solved by the you.. So, do practice for those questions. [math]Kinematics[/math]Kinematics is the most important unit of Physics. Most of the students find this chapter easy and interesting. Problems based on finding Range, Maximum height, Time of flight, velocity at any point on the trajectory are considered important in Physics. Make notes of all important formulas, theorems and derivations. This will help you in your last-minute preparation. Clear all your concepts of displacement, acceleration, average velocity, relative velocity. [math]Heat & Thermodynamics[/math]Clear all your basics related to this chapter of physics. Clear all your concepts of Zeroth law of Thermodynamics, Joules law, and First law of Thermodynamics. Practice some model papers on Carnot engine – Efficiency and Coefficient of performance. Kinetic theory of gasses is the easy and simple topic and questions from this topic which can be solved easily. [math]Modern Physics[/math] (very very very important)Modern Physics is one of the most important and scoring topic of Physics. Start with the topics such as radioactive decay of substances, nuclear fission and fusion, dual nature of matter, X-rays and Bohr’s model. To clear all your basic concepts, you should refer NCERT book. For theory part, refer “DC pandey”(my personal opinion) also you can used HC verma too.. And for numerical problems refer “USS“. And another important thing is- Solve and revisePractice and more practiceStay healthyKeep distance from toxic peopleStay positiveIn my 1st attempt i got marks less than 40,i guess it was 37 or something.. I improved my marks from 37 to 100+. I was dumb in physics.. And If I can do this then why not you. So just remember you can do anything.. Yes it's possible . Hope, the above-mentioned preparation tips will ease out your Physics Preparation and will also help you to overcome your fear for Physics subject. If you need some help or have any queries related to this, you can ask in the comment section given below. I hope it helps:-)

My physics score NEET 2018 - 50 NEET 2019 - 148 Things I did to achieve this -   Make a sheet for every chapter which has all the formulas, important numbers, units etc. It should be elaborate enough so that one reading is sufficient for you to revise the whole chapter and you're able to solve questions of every topic.It saved me the hassle of referring to my notes and this way I was sure I covered everything quickly. Books I used - selected questions from Ncert and DC Pandey + question bank of Allen's and Aakash’s modules.Edit - Previous year questions are must For physics, you should practice a variety of questions. HC Verma is a great book with seriously challenging questions but I feel it is not necessary for NEET. Never leave calculations or use calculator while practicing questions. Make a habit of doing as many calculations as you can mentally. You'll thank yourself for this during the exam because every second matters.Set goals for the next day, the night before. Continue doing this throughout the year. Ticking them off is the best feeling ever! Give dedicated hours to physics everyday. I used to finish my biology and chemistry work by 5 or 6 pm. Then I gave undivided attention to physics till I slept.Do questions in a limited time frame even while practicing. Try to be more accurate than to focus on solving all questions in that period.Lastly, stick to the basics. You shouldn't forget silly things like SI units, dimensional analysis, conversions. NEET mostly asks questions that are directly formula based and sometimes reasoning based. Don't get caught up in doing extremely difficult problems.If you believe you can do it, you're halfway there. Put in the work and you'll surely see the desired outcome. Thank you for reading!

From my point of view and experience you must go through the following things:- 1) Clear your concepts The most important thing in physics is to clearly understand the concepts and not mug up anything. As I already said above, physics is more of practical application and numerical than theory. The theory is important while you are fist learning the stuff. Also in NEET few theoretical questions also come often and it is imperative you answer those correctly because they are one of few 'free-hits' on the paper. But after you read it a few times, don’t try to remember the things line by line. Rather in your mind make a clear picture of what you learned and how many problems and types of question can be made from this portion. Try approaching the theory from different aspects of practical life. 2) Practise Numerical You need to practice a lot of numerical on all the topics in physics. As all of you may already know that about 80% of the physics paper in NEET is solely compromised by numerical. Start practising numericals on a specific topic even before you complete reading the entire chapter maybe. Whenever you learn a new law or formula, practise a few numericals on it to get the hang of the formula. Without practising numericals you will never be able to apply the formula in the examination hall. It is almost impossible for average students to directly apply the formula in the test if they are not acquainted with the type sums and problems that are related to the formula or law. 3) Work on your timing Time management is everything in NEET. Without proper time management and a lot of practice at using time efficiently, you won’t make it even if you have heaps of knowledge and skills. You get 180 minutes to solve 180 questions. That is almost impossible without a lot of practice. For biology, there are 90 questions and 45 questions each in physics chemistry. Going by the simple calculation, we must denote 1 minute for every question. But that is almost impossible for many of physics problems where a considerable amount of calculations are needed to be done. So what can you do? My personal suggestion is to save time from biology and try to give it to physics and chemistry if the need arises. Take 60 minutes for solving 90 questions in biology. This gives you 30 minutes extra to distribute between physics and chemistry. Now distribute this evenly between physics and chemistry. Ideally, take 60 minutes for physics. Now to save time, make a mental choice of the toughest or the lengthiest 5-6 questions which you won't even try. This makes the counter of 40 questions in 60 minutes. Now you have 50% more time for every physics question than what is generally allotted. So you attempt 160 in physics out of 180 marks, out of which you still have almost a 20 marks cushion which you can unsure of whether they will be right or not. Isn’t the equation looking more feasible now? 4) Cover all chapters All chapters are important for the exam. In NEET they try to evenly distribute the questions from all chapters. So don’t leave out any chapter. You may have some better preparation for the chapters from which more number of questions come, but even if you miss just 2 questions from an easy chapter that you may have thought too insignificant to pay any attention to can be a disastrous loss. 5) Follow the correct books The NCERT books may seem too easy for questions to come from there, but it is of paramount importance that you know the in and out of your NCERT books before appearing for NEET. For reference books, Arihant publication is a safe choice. They have books both for theory and MCQs. Dinesh is also good for medical aspirants. 6) MCQ, MCQ, & MCQ Mcq or multiple choice questions are the questions in which 4-5 options are given for a question and one of them is the right answer. It is almost a form of art, to correctly answer such questions. Even such situations arise when you don’t know the answer definitely and you are to determine the best possible option which you think can be right. This power of guessing right grows stronger and stronger with more and more practice. So leave everything and just go on practising MCQs. 7) Make a list Make a list of all the important formulas and also of the typical and peculiar type of problems which you tend to get wrong most of the times. Make a list so that you don’t need to go through the entire book the day before the exam. You get a very very little time before the exam. So the more you can incorporate into your list, the more the formulas will be fresh in your mind in the real exam. And the fresher they are, the more prompt you will be thus saving time. 8) Follow previous year questions To know the type and pattern of question that has been coming for the past 10 years are important to guess what can come in the exam you are going to sit. You must be able to do at least 95% of the questions that have come in the past 10 years and also the questions that are similar to them. Some of the areas of focus are Kinematics, NLM, Thermodynamics, Heat, Optics, and Waves and that would be only possible when you are conceptually strong. 9) Regular mock tests Sit for mock tests regularly. This would not only help you gain the confidence and remove your exam fever, it will also give you an idea what problems you face during a test so that you can work on resolving them. 10) Be fearless Last but not the least, don’t be afraid of physics. It is not such a big deal and you have more than enough grey matter to tackle the physics questions in NEET. Go to the examination hall fearlessly and let your brain work freely without your anxiety and fear dragging it back. . Hope these points will be helpful to you!! Good luck :)

Hi! So here goes my personal experience: I have done my coaching from Aakash institutes for 11th and 12th. During my 2 years there, I never once scored anything above 150 in physics in any 720 marks paper, ever. I assumed maybe physics wasnt meant for me, and that i could totally overcome my shortcoming by performing better in biology and chemistry. But, in neet, i ended up scoring 160 in physics. Answering your question, strengthening your basics and concepts and solving the question on time, without any silly calculative or otherwise mistakes, is the key to scoring 150+ in neet. Strenghthen your basics first. For that you can use H. C. VERMA for NLM related questions and G. C. AGARWAL for other topics. After that, to make sure that concept is etched forever in your memory, you gotta practice a whole lotta MCQs. You can use DLP or classroom course modules, Errorless, previous years’ question bank and other good mcq books for that. Encircle the questions that you couldnt solve in the first attempt and practice them repeatedly. DO NOT USE A CALCULATOR. This will help you increase your speed while calculating, doing a lot of questions on the same formula will help you to remember it, and that practice will give you an edge of perfection. Ask your teachers to help you out wherever you feel the need to get some. And, never lose faith in yourself! :) Hope that helps!

Hi there,I myself got 140 in NEET 2019 so I will share my strategy. PREPARATION TIPS The 1st and foremost thing is you have to understand the concept accurately and that can be achieved by solving as many mcqs as you can.You should make a different copy for just the formulas(Chapter wise) .And revise it almost every day and before solving mcq .Solve all the last year's NEET question and get an idea of the difficulty level.If you are taking coaching then you probably have come accross some super difficult question in their exam or study material,which are of no use for medical exam .NEET physics is a lot easier than coaching center physics questions.Don't just waste your time in solving those questions as it only accounts for 5/45 questions.Always revisit your mistakes in way of solving the question and try to find out smarter and quicker ways to solve as TIME matters in NEET.You will have to attend atleast 40 questions with precision.I attended 40 and got 4 incorrect even though I was sure.Give as many MOCK tests as you can.EXAM TIME TIPS On exam day take a light meal,or else you will jumble up at calculation.Don't panic if you can't answer the 1st question. Be mentally prepared to omit out the tough ones .There will be questions in NEET which will test your alertness and not knowledge. So be ALERT.For example, there will be a question where the answer is zero but you will do a lot of calculation spending your precious time ultimately doing it incorrectly.I did physics after completing other 2 subjects.Some students like to do it at first.Its your choice when you want to do .Try to solve within 70–80 minutes.Mark your OMR at the end (Keep half an hour for OMR ).Before again check each questions,confirm and then encircle your OMR.This helped correct 3 of my questions.FINALLY ALL THE BEST . DON'T PANIC IN THE EXAM.REMEMBER NEET NOT ONLY TESTS YOUR KNOWLEDGE AND SKILLS IN STUDIES,BUT ALSO YOUR PATIENCE AND ATTITUDE IN STRENUOUS SITUATION. HAPPY STUDYING 😉

In order to score high in physics, you need to first shed their fears and dislike for the subject. 🙂 Once you start understanding the subject, learning its formulae will not be a big deal. You can then easily implement those formulae in questions also. However what is most important is understanding the physics question and you can do that only when you have a firm grasp of concepts. Tips Have conceptual clarity: First, you have to clear the concepts without which you will not be able to move further to solve the numerical problems. So, the NCERT books are the best for clearing of the concepts. You can read from NCERT and solve the chapter end questions. You can also refer to HC Verma’s Concepts of Physics book. Read one chapter from NCERT and then you can read that chapter from HC Verma.examples - graphs   Practise MCQs to build speed and accuracy: After clearing the concepts, you can practice the numerical questions. This way you will also know how much of the theory you understood. Solve all the previous papers to get the idea of the kind of questions that will be in the exam. Have self-written notes: After learning the concepts, try to write notes in your own words so that you know how much you have understood from the book. Also, it will be easier to revise from the notes as it will be in your own language.  Seek help: When you are stuck somewhere or you have any doubt then you can always ask your friends or your teachers. Revise formulae: Learn all the formulas as most of the questions in the exam for Physics will be numerical only.All the best [1] images Footnotes[1] #Thermonuclear #Fusion #Illustration by #Physics #Teacher #Yuri #Kovalenok #jurij0001 | Physics concepts, Physics experiments, Learn physics

physics for neet aspirants has always been analogous to some monstrous creature of the dark world .one needs special spiritual  power to tackle it . not really! physics demands a little more wooing initially than other subjects but once you start understanding the concepts you start enjoying it the most . I will give you my example . back in class 12th I was scared of numericals and was extremely inconfident of my physics, as a result I attempted  a total of 5 questions in mains paper and got 3 of em right. fast  forward to this year I got 161 in physics in my neet paper and 84 in mains in the online mode which btw is tougher than offline mode. In case you are wondering I had both maths and bio in class 12th as core subjects (yeah, wasn’t  I mentally disturbed  to do that) so how did this magic happened ? well to start with I got taught with a great teacher in resonance ,this induced my interest in the subject. this is foremost requirement for scoring good in physics (if you don't have interest try to develop it) developing  good  concepts is essential for solving numericals. this I guess  is the most common mistake committed by us , we try to jump to numericals without mastering the concepts` DONT DO THAT` pay equal time to concepts and numericals. that's it once you have developed concepts  on a topic all  you need to do is practice practice and more practice .solve at least 40 good questions daily from your module/book. you are all set to score 150+ . all the best!

I scored 161 in physics this year. So, lets see the books and strategy. Any book can be sufficient, but if your physics is weak then go for DC Pandey/ errorloess. If you scored more than 100 this year, then go for McGrawHill. Stay away from HCV for the time being. Buy only the mechanics and electricity part for MGH, for rest of the chapters do neet, jee mains and advance previous year questions. Now lets come to the preparation part, try to think before you solve any question, do not jump on to questions, but study it carefully before pouncing on it. You are a tiger, the question your prey, you have a single chance, and you can’t miss that, so study your prey carefully. See what has been given, which concept is valid and which one is invalid. Which formula can been used, how many chapters have been intermixed in the question. After studying all this, then start solving. All this is called qualitative solving of a question. It is extremely helpful in mechanics, fluids, elasticity, optics, thermodynamics, electricity, magnetism, SHM and waves. For rest of the thermal physics and modern physics quantity is more important, so do accordingly. Do not see solutions right away, but try the question atleast 3 times before seeing the solution. Also, do not mark any important questions, rather whatever new you learn, write it in a notebook, not the whole question but the concept/ formula/ fusion of topics involved and the approach to solve it. Better confirm from the solution before writing this as manyatimes we tend to understand the wrong things. As you can see, this strategy requires a lot of time, around 3 hours a day for physics alone, so, manage accordingly. I hope this helps. SD
